<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-128-190  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 128 190.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Oct 2 1989 v3 n40 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Desktop III delayed for second round of best-and-final offers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Air Force accepted a second round of final offers on its $1billion Desktop III contract and extended the tri-service awarddate from Oct 1 to Oct 31, 1989.andP;  No explanation was given for thechanged contract schedule by the Air Force Standard SystemsCenter, but bidders said it had to do with the amount of foreignparts in the microcomputers being offered by vendors.andP;  The BuyAmerican and Trade Agreement laws require a certain percentage ofthe machines to be American-made and a request for a waiver onIntel Corp's Malaysia-made math co-processor chip was denied.andO;Some bidders were concerned that the second chance on biddingwould cause some companies to take advantage of leaked pricinginformation from the first offers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersGovernment ContractsLegal IssuesForeign ManufactureUnited States. Air Force.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>